ing the\nDay's Weather the Up and Down.\nWhen lie linds where the Wind is, he\n\u25a0will go and write It down in his Diary,\nwhere be has Complete Statistics for\nevery day since Hector was a Pup. If\nanybody ever discovers a use for old\nWeather Reports, he will make a\nCleaning.\nPlaying Mother and Father to His Baby Brother\nThis Is a common sight In Poland today, eight and ten-year-old children\nmothering and fathering their baby brothers and sisters. This photograph,\nsecured by an American Jewish Relief worker ai Brcst-I.itovsk, shows an\neight-year-old boy feeding his little brother from a bowl of hot soup just\nsecured at a feeding station supported through American funds. The relief\nworkers fonnd 10,000 children, mostly war orphans, living In deserted dug-outs,\nat Brest-Utovsk.\nIt is to aid such waifs as these that the European Relief Council has\nbeen formed by merging the relief activities of the American Relief Admin\nistration, the American Red Cross, the American Friends\u2019 Service Committee\n(Quakers), the Federal Council of the Churches of Christ In America, the\nJewish Joint. Distribution Committee, the Knights of Columbus, the Y. M. C. A.\nsad the I. W. C. A.\nAN APPEAL TO THE AMERICAN PEOPLE\nc\nThree and ono-f.nlf million children In Eastern and Central Europe have\nno alternative to disaster between dew and next harvest except American aid.\nFor mouths these most helpless sufferers in the ttVick of war have been ad\nmitted tc Amerhan feeding-stations only If tragically undernourished, and\nhave received American medical aid only If desperately threatened by death\nfrom disease.\nWinter Is closing down. The money of many nations Is valueless outside\ntheir own boundaries. Economic and crop conditions make famine, with its\nterrible tr.Mn of diseases, a certain visitor until next harvest. Inevitably the\nhelpless children will suffer most. No child can grow to health and sanity on\nthe pitiful makeshifts for food with which millions of European adults must\ncontent themselves this winter. It is obvious that the remedy can come only\nfrom outside.\nAmerica saved 6,000,000 European children winter bkfare Inst. Normal\nrecuperation cut ti e need nearly in half last year, hnt unusual conditions have\nresulted in scant shrinkage of child destitution during the, twelvemonth Just\npast. The lesponse of America must now decide whether' 3,ftfO.Oou of these\ncharges. In acute distress, shall begin to he turned away in January from\nmore than 17,000 asylums, hospitals, clinics and feeding-stations dependent\non American support. There would be no tragedy in history so sweeping or\nso destructive of llioee who can deserve no evil.\nTl'lie undersigned organizations, working among every race arid creed,\nmany engaged also In oilier forms of relief, agree unanimously that Hie\nplight of these helpless children should lune complete priority ill overseas\ncharity until the situation is met. Tills Is an issue without politics and\nwithout religious lines. There can he no danger of pauperization, for the\n623,000.000 fpr child food, and the $HM'<HMXi:t for medical service that we\nseek, will relieve only the critical cases. The medical supplies, of course,\nmust lie an unqualified gift, hnt for every Anglican dolin\u2019 used in child\nfeeding. the governments and communities aided furnish u\\. dollars In the\nform of transportation, rent, labor, clerical help, cash contributions and such\nfood supplies as arc locally obtainable.\nAmerica has not failed in the past In great heartedness, site lias never\nhad a more poignant call than this. Contributions should lie turned over la\nthe local committees which are now being formed for this national collection,\n\u2022r sent to Fruukliu K. Lune, Treasurer. Giiuranty Trust Co. New York City.\nEUROPEAN RELIEF COUNCIL\nHerbert Hoover, Chairman\nFranklin K. Lane. Treasurer\nComprising:\nAmerican Relief Administration, by Kd\ngar Richard. Director\nAmerican Red Cross, by Livingsto